<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
<taxonomicName authority="Berg, 1886: 212" authorityName="Bar" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Palustra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Palustra uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Palustra uruguayensis Berg, 1886: 212</taxonomicName>
Fig. 25
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="current identity">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Current identity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Paracles uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
(Berg, 1886) is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles vulpina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpina">Paracles vulpina</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hübner">Huebner</normalizedToken>
, [1825]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="material">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Described on the basis of a single female specimen from Respublica uruguayensis [Republic of Uruguay] Montevideo (Uruguay).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="type locality">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Montevideo [Uruguay].</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="macn">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">MACN.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
In the Berg collection there is a female specimen with a white label which reads &quot;Montev[ideo] Arechavaleta col,&quot; a red label with the inscription 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“TYPUS,”">&quot;TYPUS,&quot;</normalizedToken>
a white label with the inscription 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Typus,”">&quot;Typus,&quot;</normalizedToken>
a white label that reads &quot; 
<taxonomicName authority="Bar, 1873" authorityName="Bar" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Palustra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Palustra uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Palustra uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
arctiadae&quot; (handwritten by Berg) and a red label with the inscription &quot;Holotype ♀ 
<taxonomicName authority="Bar, 1873" authorityName="Bar" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Palustra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Palustra uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Palustra uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
Berg.&quot; According to the original description, this female is the holotype. We labelled it and herewith recognize it as the holotype [MACN]. It is in good overall condition (Fig. 25).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
This species was synonymized with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles vulpina" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpina">Paracles vulpina</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hübner">Huebner</normalizedToken>
, [1825]) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson, GF" journalOrPublisher="London" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" title="Catalogue of the Lepidoptera Phalaenae in the British Museum" year="1901">Hampson (1901</bibRefCitation>
: 448). Superficially, the figures of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Antarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Antarctia vulpina" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpina">Antarctia vulpina</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hübner">Huebner</normalizedToken>
and the holotype of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Paracles uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
Berg have quite different appearances. The head and thorax of the male 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Antarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Antarctia vulpina" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulpina">Antarctia vulpina</taxonomicName>
are bright red brown, the axis of the antenna is white; the abdomen has an orange dorsum. The forewing is bright red brown, the costal edge is yellowish white, and the cilia are white at the tips. The hindwings are white, the base of the inner area has some orange hair, the costa and veins towards the apex are brownish. The forewing of the female has a slightly paler costa, and the cilia are not white at the tips. The hindwing is pale brown (Hampson, 1901). The holotype female of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Paracles uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
Berg has a pale grey-yellow color pattern. The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles laboulbeni" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laboulbeni">Paracles laboulbeni</taxonomicName>
(Bar, 1873). Therefore, we propose the two taxa are valid species with the following recombination: 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Paracles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracles uruguayensis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruguayensis">Paracles uruguayensis</taxonomicName>
(Berg, 1886), sp. rev.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
